07136nam a22011055i 9789048541003DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485410037 a10.1515/97890485410032doi  a(DE-B1597)576359  a(OCoLC)1245665799  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aN6754b.C66 2021 7aART0150802bisacsh04a709.422300aContamination and Purity in Early Modern Art and Architecture /ced. by Lauren Jacobi, Daniel Zolli. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aVisual and Material Culture, 1300 –1700 ;v2700tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction: Contamination and Purity in Early Modern Art and Architecture -- t1. Generation and Ruination in the Display of Michelangelo’s Non-finito -- t2. The Sacrilege of Soot : Liturgical Decorum and the Black Madonna of Loreto -- t3. Sedimentary Aesthetics -- t4. ‘Adding to the Good Silver with Other Trickery’ : Purity and Contamination in Clement VII’s Emergency Currency -- t5. Tapestry as Tainted Medium: Charles V’s Conquest of Tunis -- t6. Bruegel’s Dirty Little Atoms -- t7. Leakage, Contagion, and Containment in Early Modern Venice -- t8. Contamination, Purification, Determinism: The Italian Pontine Marshes -- t9. Colonial Consecrations, Violent Reclamations, and Contested Spaces in the Spanish Americas -- t10. Contamination / Purification -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe concepts of purity and contamination preoccupied early modern Europeans fundamentally, structuring virtually every aspect of their lives, not least how they created and experienced works of art and the built environment. In an era that saw a great number of objects and people in motion, the meteoric rise of new artistic and building technologies, and religious upheaval exert new pressures on art and its institutions, anxieties about the pure and the contaminated - distinctions between the clean and unclean, sameness and difference, self and other, organization and its absence - took on heightened importance. In this series of geographically and methodologically wide-ranging essays, thirteen leading historians of art and architecture grapple with the complex ways that early modern actors negotiated these concerns, covering topics as diverse as Michelangelo's unfinished sculptures, Venetian plague hospitals, Spanish-Muslim tapestries, and emergency currency. The resulting volume offers surprising new insights into the period and into the modern disciplinary routines of art and architectural history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aArchitecture, European. 0aArchitecture, Renaissance. 0aArt, European. 0aArt, Renaissance. 0aContamination (Psychology). 0aPurity (Philosophy). 4aArchitecture and the Built Environment. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aArt.  aarchitecture.  acontamination.  amaterials.  apurity.1 aDean, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarpster, Grace, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoughteling, Sylvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobi, Lauren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobi, Lauren, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJones, Caroline A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoerner, Joseph Leo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c